---
import "../styles/global.css";
import "../styles/index.css";
import Animation from "../components/Animation_lesson5.tsx";
import ProgressBar from "./progressbar.astro";
---

<html>
  <head>
    <link
      rel="icon"
      type="image/png"
      href="/DiET_teaching_blog_hdfs//favicon-h.png"
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <ProgressBar step={4} total={4} />
    <h1 style="text-align: center;">HDFS block storage animation</h1>
    <p class="py-8 max-w-[1000px] mx-auto">
      You have seen what HDFS is, how it is used, how files are
      split into blocks, and how those blocks are stored on the DataNodes. Below,
      you will see the full animation, where you can select how many files you want
      to store, which DataNode to connect to, and what storage looks like
      and where the blocks are placed. Now, try different scenarios and
      see what happens. <br>
      The only new feature is the block mapping inside the NameNode, which shows where the replicas of all the blocks are stored for each file.
      <!-- Click Next to finish. -->
    </p>

    <Animation client:load />

    <!-- References to previous and next page -->
    <div class="flex justify-center gap-4 mt-6">
      <a
        href=".."
        class="px-4 py-2 text-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)] rounded-lg hover:bg-[oklch(0.6831_0.1558_356.93)] border-2 border-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)]"
      >
        Back Home
      </a>

      <a
        href="../lesson4/"
        class="px-4 py-2 text-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)] rounded-lg hover:bg-[oklch(0.6831_0.1558_356.93)] border-2 border-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)]"
      >
        Previous
      </a>

      <!-- <a
        href="../lesson6/"
        class="px-4 py-2 bg-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)] text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-[oklch(0.6831_0.1558_356.93)] border-2 border-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)]"
      >
        Next
      </a> -->
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
